100723539.100049700:
Coronary artery bypass graft (CABG) is an open surgical procedure in which one or more conduit vessels (ie. grafts) are used to bypass one or more blocked coronary arteries.
CABG surgeries performed in both isolation as well as in conjunction (concomitantly) with another cardiac surgery (excluding valve repair or replacement procedure) in the same operative (Operating Room) visit should be counted as a CABG surgery.
Aborted surgeries in which the skin incision has been made with the intent to perform the CABG, however is abandoned prior to completion should still be captured as the surgery was started.

100723543.100049700:
Coronary artery bypass graft (CABG) performed with concomitant valve repair/replacement surgery in the same operative (operating room) visit.
Aborted surgeries in which the skin incision has been made with the intent to perform a concomitant CABG and valve replacement/repair surgery, however is abandoned altogether prior to completion of either surgery should still be captured as the surgery was started. If only one of the CABG or valve replacement/repair is completed, this should be reported in the funding category that reflects the completed procedure.

100723545.100049700:
A valve repair surgery is an open surgical procedure in which the diseased/damaged native valve is manipulated with the intent to restore function. A valve replacement surgery is an open surgical procedure where the diseased/damaged native valve is excised and replaced with a tissue or mechanical valve.
Valve replacement/repair surgeries performed in both isolation as well as in conjunction (concomitantly) with another cardiac surgery (excluding CABG surgery) in the same operative (Operating Room) visit should be counted as a valve surgery.
Aborted surgeries in which the skin incision has been made with the intent to perform the valve replacement/repair, however is abandoned prior to completion should still be captured as the surgery was started.

100723547.100049700:
An other open heart surgery is an open cardiac surgical procedure, that is not performed concomitantly with a CABG or valve replacement/repair surgery. This would include aortic surgery, aneurysmectomy, cardiac tumour excision, arrhythmia surgery (i.e., Maze procedure), etc. This would exclude re-operations for exploration, bleeding, etc. due to complications to an original cardiac surgery in the same hospital visit.
LVAD, laser lead, CPR and limb amputations are not other open heart surgeries and should be excluded from this category.
'Other open heart surgery' performed concomitantly with a CABG, CABG and valve, or valve surgery in the same operative (Operating Room) visit should be reported under those funding categories. These should not be counted under 'other open heart surgery'.

100723553.100049700:
An automatic implantable cardioverter-defibrillator (AICD) is a device implanted under the skin which will deliver an electrical charge to the heart in the event of sudden cardiac arrest. (Terminates heart rates that are too fast and cause sudden cardiac death)
Aborted procedures in which the device has not been implanted are excluded and should not be counted.
A new implant is a de novo implantation of an ICD in a patient who has never had an ICD in the past.
A patient who had a previous pacemaker who receives an ICD is considered a new implant.

100723554.100049700:
A replacement is defined as one of the below:
1) a device is replaced with a device of the same type, for example, a dual chamber device is replaced with a dual chamber device. No new leads are implanted.
2) the device is replaced with a more advanced device, for example, a single chamber device is replaced with a dual chamber device, or an ICD device replaced with a CRT device.
As an example, the device is explanted due to patient complications (ie. infection), and re-implanted at a later time.

100723556.100049685: AICDs - Replacements done at Supplier's request

100723559.100049700:
Cardiac catheterization is a diagnostic cath lab procedure performed to investigate the presence and extent of coronary artery disease by coronary angiography and/or measure pressures within the heart by right heart catheterization.
A coronary angiogram may include the following: 
 - Left ventriculogram (to assess left ventricular function); and/or
 - Aortogram (to assess the anatomy of aorta).
Aborted procedures in which the skin has been punctured, but is abandoned prior to completion of the intended procedure should still be captured as the procedure was started.

100723564.100049700:
Percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) is a cath lab procedure performed to restore blood flow to the heart with balloon angioplasty and/or coronary stent implantation.
Aborted procedures in which the skin has been punctured, but is abandoned prior to completion of the intended procedure should still be captured as the procedure was started.

100723565.100049700:
Percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) is a cath lab procedure performed to restore blood flow to the heart with balloon angioplasty and/or coronary stent implantation. When stents are used, count the number of bare metal deployed and remained in coronary artery.
Aborted procedures in which the skin has been punctured, but is abandoned prior to completion of the intended procedure should still be captured as the procedure was started.

100723566.100049700:
Percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) is a cath lab procedure performed to restore blood flow to the heart with balloon angioplasty and/or coronary stent implantation. When stents are used, count the number of drug-eluting stents deployed and remained in coronary artery.
Aborted procedures in which the skin has been punctured, but is abandoned prior to completion of the intended procedure should still be captured as the procedure was started.

100723567.100049700:
Valvuloplasty is a cath lab procedure that utilizes a balloon-tipped catheter to dilate one or more of the heart valves: 
 - aortic
 - mitral
 - tricuspid
 - pulmonic

An electrophysiology study (EPS) is a catheter-based diagnostic procedure performed to identify the site of arrhythmia. It can be performed alone or in conjunction with an ablation.
Aborted procedures in which the skin has been punctured, but is abandoned prior to completion of the intended procedure should still be captured as the procedure was started.

100723570.100049700: An ablation is the delivery of energy to cardiac tissue for the purpose of correcting cardiac conduction disturbances. Aborted procedures in which the skin has been punctured, but is abandoned prior to completion of the intended procedure should still be captured as the procedure was started. A standard ablation procedure is a therapeutic technique whereby either radiofrequency (RF) energy or cryothermy is delivered from the tip of a catheter to cardiac tissue. The procedure time is less than 4 hours and an advanced mapping system is not required.

100723571.100049700: A complex ablation procedure is a therapeutic technique whereby either radiofrequency (RF) energy or cryothermy is delivered from the tip of a catheter to cardiac tissue, and exceeds 4 hours of procedure time or involves a complex mapping system.

100723574.100049700:
A new implant is a de novo implantation of a pacemaker in a patient who has never had a pacemaker in the past.
A replacement is defined as one of the below:
1) a device is replaced with a device of the same type. No new leads are implanted.
2) the device is replaced with a more advanced device.
As an example, the device is explanted due to patient complications (ie. infection), and re-implanted at a later time.
Aborted procedures in which the device has not been implanted are excluded and should not be counted.

100723579.100049700: Transcatheter aortic valve implantation (TAVI) is a minimally invasive repair of the aortic valve where a prosthetic valve (self-expanding or balloon expandable) is delivered via specialized catheter delivery system in the site of diseased aortic valve. The diseased valve is not excised.

100723584.100049700: A percutaneous catheter-based procedure where a device (i.e., clip) is delivered to the mitral valve position and clipping the two leaflets together for the treatment of mitral regurgitation.
